==English==
{{wikipedia|Mea culpa}}

===Etymology===
From the {{etyl|la|en}} phrase {{m|la|meā culpā||through my fault}}, from {{m|la|mea||my, mine}} and {{m|la|culpa||fault}} in the [[Appendix:Glossary#ablative case|ablative]]

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|en|/ˌmeɪ.əˈkʊl.pə/|/ˌmeɪ.əˈkʌl.pə/|/ˌmiː.əˈkʊl.pə/|/ˌmiː.əˈkʌl.pə/}}

===Interjection===
{{head|en|interjection|head=mea culpa}}

# My [[fault]], due to my [[error]]; I am to [[blame]].

===Noun===
{{en-noun|s|mea culpae|head=mea culpa}}

# An instance of [[mea culpa]]; an [[apology]].
#* {{quote-web|en|date=January 13, 2018| work=Civil Beat |title=When There’s Nuke Headed Your Way, ‘Do What You Gotta Do’|author=Tad Bartimus|passage= Basketball had been replaced by breathless commentators cross-talking and speculating, politicians on split screens eagerly interrupting each other to find scapegoats, and most mute (male) state officials, including Hawaii Gov. David Ige, opening their mouths to sputter (paraphrasing here) — golly gee, we don’t know what happened, but we plan to find out — '''mea culpas'''.}}

